---
import BaseLayout from "../../layouts/BaseLayout.astro";
---

<BaseLayout>
  <h1>Improving a design system’s UX</h1>
  <p>
    The goal of this project was to evaluate and improve the UX of the design
    system I was working on. The project focused on the design system’s two main
    user groups: designers and developers. There was most room for improvement
    with regards to the UX of designers, so that’s what I’ve chosen to focus on
    here.
  </p>
  <h2><span>Step 1.</span> Quantitative research</h2>
  <p>
    My first step was to send out an anonymous survey to all product designers.
  </p>
  <p>
    The aim was to find out whether the design system was living up to key
    objectives across various areas.
  </p>
  <p>
    The survey consisted of 17 questions across the five categories listed here.
  </p>
  <ul>
    <li>
      <h3>General</h3>
      <blockquote>
        It's clear what the design system’s single source of truth is, when it
        comes to components, design tokens, guidelines, etc.
      </blockquote>
    </li>
    <li>
      <h3>Finding and using components</h3>
      <blockquote>
        It's clear what to do when a component doesn't exist or doesn't meet all
        my requirements.
      </blockquote>
    </li>
    <li>
      <h3>Contributing</h3>
      <blockquote>
        I feel welcome to contribute new or improved components.
      </blockquote>
    </li>
    <li>
      <h3>Help and communication</h3>
      <blockquote>
        The design system team replies to questions and comments in a clear and
        helpful way.
      </blockquote>
    </li>
    <li>
      <h3>How can we do better?</h3>
      <blockquote>
        What's the most important thing the design system team should do
        differently?
      </blockquote>
    </li>
  </ul>
  <h2><span>Step 2.</span> Qualitative research</h2>
  <p>
    My second step was to interview every designer about the results of the
    survey.
  </p>
  <p>The goal was to get more detailed insight into the discovered issues.</p>
  <p>
    The main questions I asked for every issue, can be seen here. To get a more
    complete picture, I also asked more general questions about their
    experiences with the design system.
  </p>
  <ul>
    <li>
      <h3>Have you experienced this issue?</h3>
      <p>
        The survey’s results showed that the designers didn’t always agree on
        whether the design system was achieving a certain key objective or not.
        As a result, for every discovered issue, I had to check whether the
        designer I was interviewing actually agreed it was an issue for them.
      </p>
    </li>
    <li>
      <h3>How and when does the issue impact your work?</h3>
      <p>
        The aim of this question was to better understand how the design system
        was failing to achieve a certain key objective within the context of a
        designer’s daily work.
      </p>
    </li>
    <li>
      <h3>How can we do better?</h3>
      <p>
        I had some ideas about how to tackle the discovered issues. However, I
        was curious to hear what the designers thought would be the best
        approach. They provided me with great input and helpful suggestions.
      </p>
    </li>
  </ul>
  <h2><span>Step 3.</span> Implement changes</h2>
  <h3>Make documentation site more designer oriented</h3>
  <p>
    A main finding was that the design system’s documentation site was too
    focused on developers.
  </p>
  <p>
    Designers felt like much of the content was too technical and they had
    difficulty finding information that was relevant to them.
  </p>
  <p>
    Several changes were made to the documentation site to address this issue.
    Some of these changes are highlighted here.
  </p>
  <ul>
    <li>
      <h3>Role-specific guideline sections</h3>
      <p>
        Before, guidelines for developers, designers, and UX writers could be
        found in a single section called “Guidelines”. Now, this section is
        split up into role-specific “Developing”, “Writing”, and “Designing”
        sections.
      </p>
    </li>
    <li>
      <h3>Icons FAQ</h3>
      <p>
        A up-to-date and single-source of truth for guidelines about how to work
        with icons had always been missing. To address this issue, I created an
        “Icons FAQ” page and added it to the “Designing” section.
      </p>
    </li>
    <li>
      <h3>Accessibility checklist for designers</h3>
      <p>
        Enabling designers to create accessible user experiences is one of the
        design system’s main goals. However, the documentation site was missing
        accessibility guidelines concerning UI design. I collaborated with
        accessibility experts to create a checklist specifically for designers.
      </p>
    </li>
    <li>
      <h3>Improve icons overview page</h3>
      <p>
        The icons overview page was cluttered, making it difficult for designers
        to scan the page and find the icon they were looking for. I cleaned up
        the page and added a link to the new “Icons FAQ” page.
      </p>
    </li>
  </ul>
  <h3>Clarify single source of truth</h3>
  <p>
    The research also revealed it was sometimes unclear for designers what the
    single source of truth was, when it came to component documentation,
    guidelines, design tokens, etc.
  </p>
  <p>
    Here you can see some of the actions that were taken to solidify the
    documentation site as the one and only source of truth.
  </p>
  <ul>
    <li>
      <h3>Shorten and simplify documentation URL</h3>
      <p>
        The documentation site is the design system’s official single source of
        truth. However, its URL was quite long and difficult to remember.
        Therefore, it was simplified and shortened to fancy.siteimprove.com.
      </p>
    </li>
    <li>
      <h3>Move guidelines to documentation site</h3>
      <p>
        Some documentation could only be found outside of the official
        documentation site. That helps explain the designers’ confusion with
        regards to the true single source of truth. Documentation that was still
        relevant and up-to-date was moved to the documentation site.
      </p>
    </li>
    <li>
      <h3>Add warnings to deprecated pages</h3>
      <p>
        Some deprecated documentation pages could not be removed, due to still
        being relevant for internal use in the design system team. Warning
        messages were added to prevent designers from consulting these pages.
      </p>
    </li>
  </ul>
  <h3>Clarify terminology and processes</h3>
  <p>
    Another main finding was that certain terminology and processes for working
    with the design system were unclear to some designers.
  </p>
  <p>
    These terms and processes had been explained informally on multiple
    occasions. However, they had never been collected in a central, easily
    accessible location.
  </p>
  <p>
    I added a general FAQ for designers to the documentation site to create such
    a knowledge repository.
  </p>
  <h4>Keep designers up-to-date</h4>
  <p>
    During the interviews, several designers expressed a desire to be kept more
    up-to-date about the latest changes and additions to the design system.
  </p>
  <p>Two initiatives were started to accommodate this request.</p>
  <ul>
    <li>
      <h5>Changelogs</h5>
      <p>
        Public changelogs were added to the documentation site. The changelogs
        are written in a manner intended to be understandable to a non-technical
        audience.
      </p>
    </li>
    <li>
      <h5>More frequent updates</h5>
      <p>
        News about the design system is now posted about more frequently in a
        Slack channel specifically for designers.
      </p>
    </li>
  </ul>
  <h4>Improve review process</h4>
  <p>
    The interviews revealed it was unclear to designers how and when to get
    their wireframes and mockups reviewed by the design system team.
  </p>
  <p>
    I discussed different options with the designers, to see what suited their
    needs best. This collaborative effort resulted in a proposal for a new
    review session format. Key characteristics of this new format are described
    here.
  </p>
  <ul>
    <li>
      <h5>Multi-disciplinary feedback</h5>
      <p>
        At the new review sessions, not just members of the design system team
        would be present, but also accessibility experts and UX writers. That
        way, designers would no longer have to schedule separate feedback
        sessions with each discipline. Another benefit is that conflicting
        feedback from the different disciplines can immediately be discussed and
        resolved.
      </p>
    </li>
    <li>
      <h5>Open for all designers</h5>
      <p>
        Multiple designers expressed an interest in attending review sessions of
        other designers. That way, they could learn from the feedback given
        during the session. It would also enable them to give their fellow
        designers feedback from a UX perspective. This would in turn strengthen
        the feedback culture within the UX team.
      </p>
    </li>
    <li>
      <h5>Optional and informal</h5>
      <p>
        The designers emphasized they didn’t want the review sessions to be
        obligatory. They didn’t feel like they always needed feedback on every
        wireframe on mockup. Furthermore, they were worried the sessions would
        be formal affairs, where their work would be judged and they had to get
        “official approval” for their designs. As a result, the plan was to make
        it clear that the sessions were optional and nothing more than an
        efficient way to get feedback from different disciplines.
      </p>
    </li>
  </ul>
  <h2><span>Step 4.</span> Presentation</h2>
  <p>The last step was to give a presentation to the designers.</p>
  <p>This presentation served multiple purposes, highlighted here.</p>
  <ul>
    <li>
      <h3>Show appreciation</h3>
      <p>
        First of all, I wanted to thank the designers for their participation in
        the project. They had invested significant time filling out the survey
        and being interviewed, which I wanted to show my appreciation for.
      </p>
    </li>
    <li>
      <h3>Share findings and changes</h3>
      <p>
        Secondly, I wanted the designers to know, that their time was well
        spent. To that end, I reiterated the project’s purpose, shared the most
        important findings, and showcased both the implemented and planned
        changes.
      </p>
    </li>
    <li>
      <h3>Request feedback</h3>
      <p>
        I was also curious to hear what the designers thought of the project and
        especially the implemented and planned changes. Thankfully, their
        initial reactions were positive.
      </p>
    </li>
    <li>
      <h3>Announce reoccurrence</h3>
      <p>
        Lastly, wanted to announce that this wasn’t the first and last project
        of its kind. The plan is to conduct a similar project every year. This
        way, the design system will iteratively become better at serving its
        users.
      </p>
    </li>
  </ul>
</BaseLayout>
